WEBVTT

00:03.003 --> 00:04.482
- Pretending that you've
been friended by God?

00:04.526 --> 00:06.267
I mean, do your followers
think that's funny?

00:06.310 --> 00:08.747
- I keep telling him
he needs to get out and play.

00:08.791 --> 00:10.314
- Ray Nicolette.

00:10.358 --> 00:12.055
He's a private investigator?

00:12.099 --> 00:13.709
- Why don't you just tell me
what this is all about?

00:13.752 --> 00:15.928
I have an empty room
in my place.

00:15.972 --> 00:17.495
I'm guessing it beats
the hell out of wherever

00:17.539 --> 00:21.456
Social Services
is planning on sending you.

00:21.499 --> 00:23.762
- Falken's been an urban legend
for almost a decade.

00:23.806 --> 00:26.374
Nobody know who he really is
beyond being a genius coder.

00:26.417 --> 00:28.158
- Lucy and I might have
made contact

00:28.202 --> 00:29.638
with someone
who knows Falken.

00:29.681 --> 00:31.988
Look...it's Falken.

00:32.032 --> 00:33.946
Cara, you got your world
with Eli

00:33.990 --> 00:37.428
where you go out for dinners
and have romantic evenings

00:37.472 --> 00:39.039
on rooftop gardens.

00:39.082 --> 00:40.170
Then you have
the God Account world.

00:40.214 --> 00:41.171
You got Miles.

00:41.215 --> 00:42.564
- Oh, hey.
I'm Nia.

00:42.607 --> 00:43.695
- Hi.

00:43.739 --> 00:44.696
[both chuckle]

00:44.740 --> 00:47.743
[gospel choir music]

00:50.311 --> 00:54.619
[upbeat music]

00:54.663 --> 01:00.190
♪

01:00.234 --> 01:03.672
- And that is the latest
drop from DJ Trek,

01:03.715 --> 01:05.848
also known as my friend, Nia.

01:05.891 --> 01:07.241
- Hello, hello.
- [chuckles]

01:07.284 --> 01:08.938
So before we took
a music break,

01:08.981 --> 01:11.288
you were telling me
that you're agnostic.

01:11.332 --> 01:12.507
- I am many things,

01:12.550 --> 01:14.900
but agnostic is one
of them, yes.

01:14.944 --> 01:17.642
- Wow, that's like
the Switzerland of religion.

01:17.686 --> 01:19.905
I didn't take you for one
who'd play it safe.

01:19.949 --> 01:22.343
- How is keeping an open mind
playing it safe?

01:22.386 --> 01:25.172
God or no god,
in live in the question.

01:25.215 --> 01:27.783
No need for answers.
I like the mystery.

01:27.826 --> 01:29.132
- Come on, Nia.

01:29.176 --> 01:30.786
Everyone wants to know
the truth.

01:30.829 --> 01:32.135
- And then what?

01:32.179 --> 01:33.832
What happens when you have
all the answers?

01:33.876 --> 01:35.443
Take the God Account
for example.

01:35.486 --> 01:36.966
You any closer to finding
the mystery person

01:37.009 --> 01:38.402
behind it all?

01:38.446 --> 01:39.925
- Not yet, but it's only
a matter of time.

01:39.969 --> 01:42.493
- Yeah, but what happens
when you do?

01:42.537 --> 01:45.148
What if you stop getting
Friend Suggestions?

01:47.107 --> 01:48.412
- Your point?

01:48.456 --> 01:51.676
- I know how much you like
helping people.

01:51.720 --> 01:55.245
Getting the truth
may end your journey.

01:55.289 --> 01:58.422
Maybe you can stand
a little agnosticism

01:58.466 --> 01:59.989
when it comes to
the God Account?

02:00.032 --> 02:01.730
- Way to bring it back
around.

02:01.773 --> 02:03.471
Thank you so much
for being my guest

02:03.514 --> 02:05.342
on the Millennial Prophet.

02:05.386 --> 02:08.302
You can check out more tracks
from DJ Trek on Soundcloud.

02:08.345 --> 02:11.305
[soft music]

02:11.348 --> 02:13.089
♪

02:13.133 --> 02:14.438
- Sorry.

02:14.482 --> 02:17.006
Didn't mean to put you
on the spot.

02:17.049 --> 02:19.226
- No worries.
I can take it.

02:19.269 --> 02:21.576
- I was just trying
to make the point

02:21.619 --> 02:23.665
that even if you
get your answer one day,

02:23.708 --> 02:26.189
doesn't mean you have to
stop helping people.

02:26.233 --> 02:28.800
- I won't.
- Good.

02:28.844 --> 02:31.063
So, how 'bout you keep
that promise

02:31.107 --> 02:33.718
and come with me
to the hospital this afternoon?

02:33.762 --> 02:35.894
I spin for the kids
at the pediatric center.

02:35.938 --> 02:38.027
- I'll be there.

02:45.730 --> 02:47.515
- Miles, Miles you need
to see this.

02:47.558 --> 02:48.907
- Oh.

02:50.474 --> 02:53.434
- So, FIBONACCI61
sent a picture of me and Lucy

02:53.477 --> 02:56.437
at Strawberry Fields with,
"Just wanted to say hello"

02:56.480 --> 02:57.829
as the message.

02:57.873 --> 02:59.309
I mean,
this is definitely Falken.

02:59.353 --> 03:00.745
He's definitely behind
the God Account.

03:00.789 --> 03:02.225
- Okay, I don't know.

03:02.269 --> 03:04.053
Look, whoever's behind
the God Account

03:04.096 --> 03:06.403
has gone through a whole lot
of trouble to remain anonymous.

03:06.447 --> 03:09.232
Why reach out now
by text message to you?

03:09.276 --> 03:10.494
- I don't know, Miles.

03:10.538 --> 03:11.843
Maybe because I'm getting
too close.

03:11.887 --> 03:13.105
- Yeah.

03:13.149 --> 03:14.411
- Bro, it's clear Falken's

03:14.455 --> 03:16.500
trying to back me off
by intimidation.

03:16.544 --> 03:18.415
Guess what.
- Hmm?

03:18.459 --> 03:21.766
- Nobody intimidates
Rakesh Singh.

03:21.810 --> 03:23.420
Except my mama.
She's very scary.

03:23.464 --> 03:26.249
- [laughs]
[phone buzzes]

03:28.077 --> 03:29.600
- Hey, the God Account

03:29.644 --> 03:32.516
just liked the fan page
of Graham Hastings!

03:32.560 --> 03:35.389
- Uh, never heard of him.

03:35.432 --> 03:39.175
- Graham Hastings is a
legendary Harlem chess player.

03:39.219 --> 03:41.525
Everyone thought he was gonna
be the next Bobby Fischer.

03:41.569 --> 03:43.179
Then one day,
he just disappeared

03:43.223 --> 03:44.528
from the public eye.

03:44.572 --> 03:46.443
- Hmm.
- No one has seen him since.

03:46.487 --> 03:49.185
That was ten years ago.

03:49.229 --> 03:50.882
- Wait, wait, wait, wait.

03:50.926 --> 03:54.625
So, our first Friend Suggestion
after Falken makes contact

03:54.669 --> 03:58.281
just happens to be some recluse
who disappeared ten years ago?

03:58.325 --> 03:59.804
- Graham's not Falken,
Rakesh.

03:59.848 --> 04:01.763
- I'm--I'm not saying he is,

04:01.806 --> 04:03.504
but maybe there's a connection.
- There's a rumor going around

04:03.547 --> 04:04.940
saying that Graham's gonna be

04:04.983 --> 04:06.811
at Washington Square Park
today!

04:06.855 --> 04:08.291
That must be why
the God Account

04:08.335 --> 04:09.858
sent us his name.

04:09.901 --> 04:12.600
Looks like we got our next
Friend Suggestion.

04:14.341 --> 04:16.778
- Yeah, things with Eli
are good.

04:16.821 --> 04:18.345
- So you keep saying.

04:18.388 --> 04:21.261
- 'Cause they are.
[phone chimes, buzzes]

04:25.439 --> 04:27.179
- Are you really busy
with work,

04:27.223 --> 04:30.922
or are you just bothered
because you saw Miles with Nia?

04:30.966 --> 04:32.750
- Why would that bother me?

04:32.794 --> 04:34.448
- Probably because
seeing him with her

04:34.491 --> 04:36.101
made you question
whether or not

04:36.145 --> 04:38.060
you made the right choice
to date Eli again.

04:40.018 --> 04:42.282
- Okay, fine.
I'll admit it.

04:42.325 --> 04:44.501
It was a little weird
seeing him with someone.

04:44.545 --> 04:47.287
And, yeah, okay.

04:47.330 --> 04:50.290
I may have been
the tiniest bit jealous of Nia,

04:50.333 --> 04:53.554
but I'm not questioning
my choice to be with Eli.

04:53.597 --> 04:55.338
- So why are you
avoiding Miles?

04:55.382 --> 04:56.905
- I'm not.

04:56.948 --> 04:59.342
I'm just focusing on
the assignment Natalie gave me

04:59.386 --> 05:01.388
to prove to her that
I'm worthy of that promotion.

05:01.431 --> 05:03.738
- If you say so.

05:03.781 --> 05:06.741
[soft music]

05:06.784 --> 05:10.179
♪

05:10.222 --> 05:13.269
- [humming]
[knocking at door]

05:13.313 --> 05:15.489
Ali.
- Hi.

05:15.532 --> 05:17.447
I brought you
a little souvenir

05:17.491 --> 05:19.493
from the other night.

05:19.536 --> 05:21.277
- Ohh...

05:21.321 --> 05:24.149
And here I thought
my cool days were behind me.

05:24.193 --> 05:25.412
Oh, that's lovely.
Thanks, Ali.

05:25.455 --> 05:26.804
- You're welcome.

05:26.848 --> 05:28.545
- Here.

05:28.589 --> 05:32.288
- Dad, I just wanna say

05:32.332 --> 05:34.812
I am proud of you
for having the courage

05:34.856 --> 05:36.553
to find
your love of music again.

05:36.597 --> 05:38.555
- Well, it's easy
to be courageous

05:38.599 --> 05:40.731
with my children by my side.

05:40.775 --> 05:42.472
- Well, speaking
of your children,

05:42.516 --> 05:44.169
I couldn't help but notice
you and Miles

05:44.213 --> 05:46.650
talking after your set.

05:46.694 --> 05:49.784
You guys looked like
father and son again.

05:49.827 --> 05:51.438
- [chuckles]

05:51.481 --> 05:55.485
You know, I have to admit that

05:55.529 --> 06:00.055
I haven't felt this close
to Miles since--gosh, um...

06:00.098 --> 06:01.796
Since he was a kid.

06:01.839 --> 06:04.407
I can't quite put
my finger on it,

06:04.451 --> 06:07.802
but he seems to have changed
over the last few months.

06:07.845 --> 06:10.500
- Yeah, and it's pretty obvious
what's causing it.

06:12.284 --> 06:13.982
- Not the God Account.

06:14.025 --> 06:15.375
- Dad...

06:15.418 --> 06:17.638
- Ali it's just fodder
for his podcast,

06:17.681 --> 06:20.423
a story device
to get attention.

06:20.467 --> 06:22.338
- No, it's not.

06:22.382 --> 06:25.602
Look--and even if it was,
what does it matter?

06:25.646 --> 06:28.257
At the end of the day,
he's helping people.

06:28.300 --> 06:29.911
Same as you.

06:35.220 --> 06:38.006
- So, did Cara tell you why
she can't meet us today?

06:38.049 --> 06:39.703
She's usually leading
the charge

06:39.747 --> 06:41.401
when it comes to
the God Account.

06:41.444 --> 06:43.315
- Said she was working
on a story, but no biggie.

06:43.359 --> 06:44.491
Hey, we got this.

06:44.534 --> 06:46.188
- Yeah.

06:47.842 --> 06:49.496
- Whoa.
- Whoa.

06:49.539 --> 06:50.888
- Word definitely got out

06:50.932 --> 06:52.455
that Graham
may resurface today, huh?

06:52.499 --> 06:53.935
- My dad used to tell stories

06:53.978 --> 06:56.111
about how people
would line up around the block

06:56.154 --> 06:57.765
just to get beat by Graham.

06:57.808 --> 07:00.507
He even claims
he played him once.

07:00.550 --> 07:02.334
- Well, I don't need
to play him.

07:02.378 --> 07:04.902
I just need to know what
he knows about Falken.

07:06.556 --> 07:08.210
What?
- It's Cara.

07:10.299 --> 07:13.171
- I thought she was working.
- Yeah, me too.

07:14.477 --> 07:16.087
- Guys. Sorry.

07:16.131 --> 07:17.524
What are you doing here?

07:17.567 --> 07:18.916
- I was gonna ask you
the same thing.

07:18.960 --> 07:20.570
- Well, my boss
assigned me a story

07:20.614 --> 07:22.267
about some
chess-genius-turned-recluse

07:22.311 --> 07:23.878
named Graham Hastings.

07:23.921 --> 07:25.662
What?
- Graham Hastings

07:25.706 --> 07:26.881
is our Friend Suggestion.

07:26.924 --> 07:28.317
- Yeah, y'all this is great.

07:28.360 --> 07:29.666
We get to work on this
together.

07:29.710 --> 07:32.408
- Great.

07:32.452 --> 07:34.584
- How long have you been here?

07:34.628 --> 07:36.107
- Almost an hour.

07:36.151 --> 07:37.892
Yeah, this crowd
is getting restless.

07:39.546 --> 07:41.330
- Well, looks like
they're giving up.

07:41.373 --> 07:43.593
- Ugh, what a bust.

07:43.637 --> 07:45.769
All right, well, I'm gonna
head back to work,

07:45.813 --> 07:47.467
keep on the Falken line.

07:47.510 --> 07:48.729
Okay?
- Okay.

07:48.772 --> 07:50.905
- Let me know if anything
happens.

07:55.997 --> 07:57.694
- [clears throat]

07:57.738 --> 07:59.348
- You okay?

07:59.391 --> 08:01.698
- Yeah.
Yeah, it's fine.

08:01.742 --> 08:03.004
Fine.

08:03.047 --> 08:04.440
So, how are we gonna find
someone

08:04.484 --> 08:06.529
who clearly does not
wanna be found?

08:06.573 --> 08:08.966
- Well, if it ain't
my two favorite do-gooders.

08:09.010 --> 08:10.533
[laughs]
- Ray?

08:10.577 --> 08:13.449
- Hey.
Okay, still not a hugger.

08:13.493 --> 08:15.843
- Hey, Ray.
It's good to see you.

08:15.886 --> 08:17.192
- You too, you too.

08:17.235 --> 08:18.759
So what dragged you two
down here today?

08:18.802 --> 08:21.849
- Uh, we're looking for
Graham Hastings.

08:23.328 --> 08:26.070
- Now, that's a hell
of a coincidence.

08:26.114 --> 08:27.985
- How so?

08:28.029 --> 08:31.206
- Because someone hired me
to find him.

08:33.730 --> 08:36.124
[light suspenseful
tune]

08:36.167 --> 08:38.518
♪

08:45.046 --> 08:46.700
[upbeat music]

08:46.743 --> 08:48.484
- So, how are things
with Isaac?

08:48.528 --> 08:49.964
- Isaac's doing great.

08:50.007 --> 08:51.879
I got the kid enrolled
in a good school.

08:51.922 --> 08:54.098
His teachers say
he's keeping up.

08:54.142 --> 08:57.406
I gotta tell ya, I think
he's adapting pretty good,

08:57.449 --> 08:59.843
considering everything
he's been through.

08:59.887 --> 09:02.411
[grunts]
Ah...

09:02.454 --> 09:04.108
- How 'bout you?

09:04.152 --> 09:05.545
Are you adapting?
- Eh.

09:05.588 --> 09:07.634
Still working on it.

09:07.677 --> 09:10.419
It is nice having some company
around the house again.

09:10.462 --> 09:11.638
- You're a good man, Ray.

09:11.681 --> 09:14.249
- Don't tell people that.

09:15.293 --> 09:18.209
And you still working for
the God Account thing, huh?

09:18.253 --> 09:20.124
Any closer to figuring out
who's behind it?

09:20.168 --> 09:23.606
- Not yet, but they did send
Graham Hastings our way.

09:23.650 --> 09:26.261
So, wanna tell us
who hired you?

09:26.304 --> 09:28.568
- No-ho-ho can do.

09:28.611 --> 09:30.352
What I can tell you

09:30.395 --> 09:34.008
is that Hastings is completely
off the grid.

09:34.051 --> 09:35.444
I was hoping
he'd be here today,

09:35.487 --> 09:36.837
make my job a lot easier.

09:36.880 --> 09:38.882
But as you can see, nada.

09:40.449 --> 09:42.146
- Wait a minute.

09:42.190 --> 09:44.018
You started the rumor
on that fan page

09:44.061 --> 09:46.629
about Graham playing chess
here today, didn't you?

09:46.673 --> 09:48.544
- Guilty as charged.

09:48.588 --> 09:50.546
Isaac's got me using
social media more.

09:50.590 --> 09:52.200
Thought I could lure Graham
out of hiding,

09:52.243 --> 09:53.767
but as you can see...

09:53.810 --> 09:55.638
- Nada.
- Well, look,

09:55.682 --> 09:58.685
since we're all looking for
Graham, why don't we team up?

09:58.728 --> 09:59.686
- Yeah, like old times.

09:59.729 --> 10:01.688
- Let's not get crazy.

10:01.731 --> 10:04.995
As fun as that sounds,
we all know the sequels

10:05.039 --> 10:07.171
are never as good
as the originals.

10:07.215 --> 10:09.217
I'm off, kids.

10:09.260 --> 10:12.002
And may the best
private detective

10:12.046 --> 10:13.395
with over 20 years

10:13.438 --> 10:15.702
of law enforcement
experience win.

10:18.400 --> 10:20.271
- Any thoughts
on where to start?

10:24.362 --> 10:26.713
- Actually, I do.

10:28.279 --> 10:32.806
- For God has not given us
a spirit of fear,

10:32.849 --> 10:35.330
but of power and of love...

10:35.373 --> 10:36.853
- Hey.
- And of sound mind.

10:36.897 --> 10:38.942
Miles.
[chuckles]

10:38.986 --> 10:40.944
- Dad, I want you to meet
Cara Bloom.

10:40.988 --> 10:42.250
- Oh, of course.

10:42.293 --> 10:45.688
Cara, I have heard
a lot about you.

10:45.732 --> 10:47.342
And I'm sorry we didn't
get a chance

10:47.385 --> 10:49.300
to meet the other night
- Yeah, yeah, me, too.

10:49.344 --> 10:50.519
- Please, sit down.

10:50.562 --> 10:52.173
- You were fantastic,
by the way.

10:52.216 --> 10:56.264
- Oh, thank you.
Still working off the rust.

10:56.307 --> 11:00.790
But I understand that you and I
share a connection.

11:00.834 --> 11:03.184
Your mother.

11:03.227 --> 11:05.752
- Yeah, yeah, that's right.

11:05.795 --> 11:08.668
- Susan was
an incredible nurse.

11:08.711 --> 11:11.496
Always there
when my wife needed her

11:11.540 --> 11:13.237
when she was battling cancer.

11:13.281 --> 11:16.023
A much-needed rock
for both of us.

11:18.503 --> 11:20.375
Anyway, how's she doing?

11:20.418 --> 11:21.637
- Uh, she's great.

11:21.681 --> 11:22.943
I'll let her know
you say hello.

11:22.986 --> 11:24.727
- Please do.

11:24.771 --> 11:27.817
So, to what do I owe the visit?

11:27.861 --> 11:30.254
- Do you remember
Graham Hastings?

11:30.298 --> 11:32.126
- [laughs]
Absolutely.

11:32.169 --> 11:33.736
Didn't I ever tell you that
I played against him once?

11:33.780 --> 11:35.303
- You may have mentioned it.
- Ah.

11:35.346 --> 11:38.045
Well, so, it was down
at St. Nicholas Park,

11:38.088 --> 11:39.481
and I'm setting up
the chess pieces.

11:39.524 --> 11:41.744
And this kid sits down
in front of me

11:41.788 --> 11:44.747
and asks if I wanna play.
[snaps] 12 moves.

11:44.791 --> 11:47.315
That's it took for him
to beat me--12 moves.

11:47.358 --> 11:48.620
- We heard he disappeared.

11:48.664 --> 11:50.710
Do you know what happened
to him?

11:50.753 --> 11:52.015
Or where he went?

11:53.190 --> 11:55.366
- Why the sudden interest?

11:58.239 --> 12:00.458
- Uh, I'm writing a story
for "Catapult."

12:00.502 --> 12:02.156
Miles is helping me.

12:02.199 --> 12:04.375
- Oh, well, if I were looking
for Graham Hastings,

12:04.419 --> 12:07.465
I would start with the person
that knew him the best.

12:07.509 --> 12:09.337
- Who's that?
- Aleksander Leff.

12:09.380 --> 12:11.556
Back in the day,
he and Graham

12:11.600 --> 12:15.735
were the Muhammad Ali
and Joe Frazier of chess.

12:15.778 --> 12:18.172
I always wished I had
a chance to watch them play.

12:18.215 --> 12:20.000
- So, they were rivals?

12:20.043 --> 12:21.741
- [chuckles]
Oh, man.

12:21.784 --> 12:24.526
They would meet at the finals
of every tournament.

12:24.569 --> 12:26.223
Aleksander could never
beat him.

12:26.267 --> 12:28.835
Until, of course, he did.

12:28.878 --> 12:31.838
After that,
Graham Hastings retreated

12:31.881 --> 12:33.448
and was never heard from again.

12:33.491 --> 12:35.580
- That sounds like
a poor sport.

12:35.624 --> 12:39.019
- Or he accomplished
everything he set out to.

12:39.062 --> 12:40.672
The truth is that nobody knows

12:40.716 --> 12:43.458
why Graham Hastings
disappeared.

12:44.720 --> 12:46.200
Sorry, Miles,
you'll have to excuse me.

12:46.243 --> 12:48.898
I have to set up for
an afternoon service.

12:48.942 --> 12:50.987
- Thanks, Dad.
- Good to see you.

12:51.031 --> 12:53.033
Good luck with the story.
- Thank you.

12:54.948 --> 12:57.341
Why didn't you just tell him
it was about the God Account?

12:57.385 --> 12:58.821
- 'Cause he doesn't wanna know.
[phone buzzes]

12:58.865 --> 13:00.301
Oh.

13:00.344 --> 13:02.259
I'm sorry, I have plans
with Nia.

13:02.303 --> 13:05.349
Can we meet back up later?
It'll only take a couple hours.

13:05.393 --> 13:07.177
- Yeah, of course.

13:07.221 --> 13:09.092
I'll try and track down
an address for Aleksander Leff.

13:09.136 --> 13:10.920
Text you if I find anything.
- Okay.

13:12.748 --> 13:14.445
[Calvin Harris's "Feels"]

13:14.489 --> 13:16.186
- ♪ You shock me

13:16.230 --> 13:18.145
♪ The way you move it here

13:18.188 --> 13:20.800
♪ Just wanna feel it
from you ♪

13:20.843 --> 13:22.453
♪ Hey
oo-woo ♪

13:22.497 --> 13:25.500
[giggling and applause]

13:26.457 --> 13:29.765
- Thanks, Nia!
- That was fun.

13:29.809 --> 13:31.027
- Thanks, Nia.

13:31.071 --> 13:33.682
- You're welcome, Matty.
High-five.

13:33.725 --> 13:36.772
Oh, I got something for you.

13:36.816 --> 13:38.208
Hmm...

13:38.252 --> 13:41.124
[soft music]

13:41.168 --> 13:43.474
♪

13:43.518 --> 13:45.302
Can I see your patch?

13:51.221 --> 13:55.530
Now you got
tons of street cred.

13:55.573 --> 13:57.358
[laughs]

13:57.401 --> 14:00.927
♪

14:00.970 --> 14:03.059
- What was the, uh, patch
on his arm for?

14:03.103 --> 14:05.845
- People wear them
to fight off the nausea

14:05.888 --> 14:07.934
when they're going through
chemo.

14:07.977 --> 14:09.936
Unfortunately for me,
they weren't invented

14:09.979 --> 14:11.763
till after I was cancer-free.

14:11.807 --> 14:14.766
- You were impressive
with these kids.

14:14.810 --> 14:16.290
[laughter]

14:16.333 --> 14:18.161
- Well, music was my lifeline
when I was sick.

14:18.205 --> 14:21.948
It's just my way
of giving back.

14:21.991 --> 14:25.299
♪

14:25.342 --> 14:26.909
[phone buzzes]

14:26.953 --> 14:28.955
- I'm sorry, I have to go.

14:28.998 --> 14:30.913
- God Account?
- Yeah.

14:30.957 --> 14:32.872
Yeah, we're trying to
track down

14:32.915 --> 14:34.569
this reclusive chess prodigy.

14:34.612 --> 14:36.266
- Hmm.
- I'll text you?

14:36.310 --> 14:43.317
♪

14:46.973 --> 14:48.931
Cara.
- Hey.

14:48.975 --> 14:50.454
- 'Sup?

14:55.068 --> 14:56.896
- So, how did it got
with Nia?

14:58.767 --> 15:01.988
- It went...well.

15:03.380 --> 15:04.555
- Well?
- [chuckles]

15:04.599 --> 15:05.817
- Hmm.

15:05.861 --> 15:08.081
Well,
she seems really nice.

15:10.387 --> 15:13.347
- How are things with Eli?
Things still going good?

15:13.390 --> 15:15.523
- Yeah.
Yeah, things are good.

15:15.566 --> 15:17.003
Oh, this is 18.
This is it.

15:22.312 --> 15:25.272
[soft music]

15:25.315 --> 15:29.885
♪

15:29.929 --> 15:31.365
- Aleksander Leff?

15:31.408 --> 15:32.888
- That's right.
Can I help you?

15:32.932 --> 15:34.629
- I'm Miles Finer.
This is Cara Bloom.

15:34.672 --> 15:36.152
- We were hoping to ask you
a few questions

15:36.196 --> 15:37.719
about Graham Hastings.

15:37.762 --> 15:39.677
- I'm sorry.
I don't give interview.

15:39.721 --> 15:42.898
- Let 'em in, otherwise they'll
just stand out there all day.

15:44.944 --> 15:46.815
Took you long enough.

15:54.997 --> 15:57.608
- So, why are you looking
for Graham?

15:57.652 --> 16:00.872
- I never understood why
he walked away from everything.

16:00.916 --> 16:03.701
That question has haunted me
for a decade.

16:05.442 --> 16:07.705
- I heard you two had
a pretty intense rivalry.

16:09.011 --> 16:11.318
- That's one way to look at it.

16:11.361 --> 16:14.799
The truth is,
we were best friends.

16:14.843 --> 16:16.845
Had been since we were kids.

16:16.888 --> 16:20.022
We played our first game
together when we were eight.

16:20.066 --> 16:22.982
From that moment on,
our lives were tied together.

16:24.070 --> 16:26.768
But as much as we were
the same,

16:26.811 --> 16:28.596
we came from different worlds.

16:28.639 --> 16:30.554
- What do you mean?

16:30.598 --> 16:33.209
- I grew up in privilege.

16:33.253 --> 16:35.472
My father made sure
I had the best teachers,

16:35.516 --> 16:37.735
that I studied day and night.

16:37.779 --> 16:39.172
All he had was his grandfather.

16:39.215 --> 16:41.391
Didn't have any money,
any training.

16:41.435 --> 16:44.046
Never even read a book
about chess.

16:45.439 --> 16:47.702
His talent was God-given.

16:47.745 --> 16:50.009
I couldn't help but envy that.

16:52.402 --> 16:54.535
- Now that we're all
caught up here,

16:54.578 --> 16:56.319
why don't we take this outside

16:56.363 --> 16:58.974
and have a chat about how
we're gonna find this guy, huh?

16:59.018 --> 17:02.369
- Hold on--I mean,
that was ten years ago.

17:02.412 --> 17:03.979
Why hire Ray now?

17:04.023 --> 17:06.982
[melancholy music]

17:07.026 --> 17:14.946
♪

17:14.990 --> 17:17.079
- Because you're sick.

17:17.123 --> 17:20.430
♪

17:20.474 --> 17:21.997
Aren't you?

17:24.130 --> 17:26.349
- Pancreatic cancer.

17:26.393 --> 17:29.004
Doctors say I only have
a few months left.

17:30.832 --> 17:34.096
I need to speak with Graham
before it's too late.

17:34.140 --> 17:37.795
♪

17:39.058 --> 17:42.713
- I wanna find this Graham guy,
close my case, and get paid.

17:42.757 --> 17:44.193
Any thoughts?

17:44.237 --> 17:46.674
- Yeah, we all work together.

17:46.717 --> 17:49.242
- If by "work together"
you mean "split my fee,"

17:49.285 --> 17:50.678
I must politely decline.

17:50.721 --> 17:52.114
- We're not interested in
your fee.

17:52.158 --> 17:53.855
- Then by all means, proceed.

17:53.898 --> 17:56.031
- I think the God Account
wants us to find Graham

17:56.075 --> 17:57.598
for the same reason you do.

17:57.641 --> 17:59.295
To put him in front
of Aleksander.

17:59.339 --> 18:02.646
Now any idea what he wants
to tell him?

18:02.690 --> 18:04.344
- He didn't offer,
I didn't ask.

18:04.387 --> 18:06.128
But usually when a client
wants me to track down

18:06.172 --> 18:09.044
someone from their past,
it's about making amends.

18:09.088 --> 18:10.567
- Hmm.
So, what'd you find?

18:10.611 --> 18:12.134
- Not a hell of a lot.

18:12.178 --> 18:13.701
I mean, he's off the grid
ten years,

18:13.744 --> 18:16.095
and it ain't hard to disappear
in this city.

18:16.138 --> 18:18.619
- Yeah, but people knew him.
Or at least they knew his name.

18:18.662 --> 18:20.577
In order to really disappear
he'd have to change it.

18:20.621 --> 18:22.144
- I knew I liked you.

18:22.188 --> 18:24.277
I was on that same line
of thought.

18:24.320 --> 18:26.366
I got a buddy down
at the Department of Records.

18:26.409 --> 18:29.020
I was heading over there
when you two crashed the party.

18:29.064 --> 18:31.675
What about you?
God give you any leads?

18:31.719 --> 18:33.024
- Just the fan page.

18:33.068 --> 18:34.896
- I already been there.
Full of crazies.

18:34.939 --> 18:37.159
- The God Account never does
anything random.

18:37.203 --> 18:39.205
Whoever created this fan page

18:39.248 --> 18:41.250
seems to know a lot
about Graham.

18:42.904 --> 18:46.081
Maybe we can track them down.
See if they know anything.

18:46.125 --> 18:47.822
- Makes sense.
Sounds good.

18:47.865 --> 18:49.302
You guys track down that lead,

18:49.345 --> 18:51.913
and I'll text you if I get
a new name on Graham.

18:53.175 --> 18:56.135
- You mind if I go with you?
It'd be nice to catch up.

18:56.178 --> 18:57.832
- Yeah, sure.
What the hell?

18:57.875 --> 19:00.487
- Okay, I'll head back
to IdentitySeal,

19:00.530 --> 19:03.577
see if Rakesh and I can dig up
anything on this fan page.

19:03.620 --> 19:05.492
- Okay.

19:05.535 --> 19:08.495
- You really think whoever runs
this crazy Facebook fan page

19:08.538 --> 19:10.061
actually knows where Graham is?

19:10.105 --> 19:11.498
- It's worth a shot.

19:11.541 --> 19:13.500
- How was going to the hospital
with Nia?

19:14.675 --> 19:17.982
- Good.
She's actually pretty amazing.

19:18.026 --> 19:19.549
- Yeah?

19:19.593 --> 19:21.203
You gonna start seeing her?

19:21.247 --> 19:24.293
- I haven't decided,
but I mean, I do like her.

19:24.337 --> 19:28.384
- Well, then there's nothing
holding you back.

19:29.472 --> 19:31.039
- You mean Cara?

19:31.082 --> 19:33.694
- [laughs] Was I that obvious?

19:33.737 --> 19:35.522
- Yeah.

19:35.565 --> 19:37.437
Look, she's with Eli
and she's happy.

19:37.480 --> 19:41.223
And I'm happy for her.
So, no.

19:41.267 --> 19:43.182
There's nothing
holding me back.

19:43.225 --> 19:44.444
[computer bleeps]

19:44.487 --> 19:46.359
- All right.
Cracked the admin.

19:46.402 --> 19:48.796
Looks like the page is run by
a guy named Larry Bartholomew.

19:48.839 --> 19:50.754
Owner and proprietor
of Chess Forum.

19:50.798 --> 19:53.583
- Oh, I know that place.
It's a chess shop in Harlem.

19:53.627 --> 19:55.019
I used to go with my dad
as a kid

19:55.063 --> 19:56.195
when I was learning
how to play.

19:56.238 --> 19:57.935
Come on, let's go.

19:58.762 --> 20:02.157
- So, ten years ago,
Graham Hastings

20:02.201 --> 20:04.812
changed his name
to John Turner.

20:04.855 --> 20:07.249
Kept it generic for a reason
I'm guessing.

20:07.293 --> 20:08.598
Let's see here...

20:08.642 --> 20:10.426
Oh-ho, yep.

20:10.470 --> 20:12.559
Almost 50 of 'em
in New York.

20:12.602 --> 20:14.300
- Any ideas on how
to narrow it down?

20:14.343 --> 20:16.476
- Yeah.
One at a time.

20:19.261 --> 20:21.307
- So, Isaac keeping you busy?

20:21.350 --> 20:22.917
- Oh-ho-ho-ho.

20:22.960 --> 20:24.135
- Is he a Giants fan yet?

20:24.179 --> 20:26.312
- Eh, still working on that.

20:26.355 --> 20:28.401
This season hasn't made it
any easier.

20:28.444 --> 20:30.446
[phone buzzes]

20:30.490 --> 20:31.752
- Sorry, it's just my boss.

20:31.795 --> 20:33.275
- Oh, yeah.
How's the writing?

20:33.319 --> 20:34.711
- It's really good.
- Yeah?

20:34.755 --> 20:36.017
- Yeah.

20:36.060 --> 20:37.714
I'm actually up for this
promotion,

20:37.758 --> 20:39.934
and I think that this story
about Graham Hastings

20:39.977 --> 20:41.457
might be the one
that gets it for me.

20:41.501 --> 20:43.677
- Finding a reclusive
chess genius?

20:43.720 --> 20:45.331
It sounds like a Pulitzer
to me.

20:47.855 --> 20:50.205
You know, it's nice seeing
you and Miles still together.

20:50.249 --> 20:51.511
- Oh, no.
We're just friends.

20:51.554 --> 20:52.816
Not together.

20:53.948 --> 20:55.993
- You know
you say that a lot?

20:56.037 --> 20:58.866
I'm just saying, it doesn't
take a private detective

20:58.909 --> 21:00.607
to see the chemistry.

21:00.650 --> 21:02.696
- We both know it takes more
than just chemistry.

21:02.739 --> 21:04.915
- Didn't with my wife and me.

21:04.959 --> 21:06.874
[soft music]

21:06.917 --> 21:09.398
- It's just never been
the right time for us.

21:09.442 --> 21:11.313
And now I'm seeing someone.

21:11.357 --> 21:13.359
I'm actually back together
with my ex, Eli.

21:13.402 --> 21:15.186
Things with him are good.

21:16.623 --> 21:18.973
- Well, kid, I don't know much,
but I do know this:

21:19.016 --> 21:21.323
"Good" ain't great.

21:21.367 --> 21:23.151
"Great's" what you're
shooting for.

21:23.194 --> 21:25.153
You know, when it comes to
affairs of the heart,

21:25.196 --> 21:27.982
"great" is what knocks
you on your ass

21:28.025 --> 21:29.897
and lets you know that you can
stop looking.

21:29.940 --> 21:32.813
Miles aside, if you're happy
with this Eli guy, fine.

21:32.856 --> 21:35.337
But if you're just buying time,

21:35.381 --> 21:37.470
waiting for "great"
to come along,

21:37.513 --> 21:40.081
you should do you both
a favor and keep looking.

21:45.129 --> 21:46.914
[phone buzzing]

21:49.699 --> 21:52.572
- Graham changed his name
to John Turner.

21:59.405 --> 22:02.190
- Here to play or purchase?
- Actually, neither.

22:02.233 --> 22:04.410
- We're wondering about
your Graham Hastings fan page.

22:04.453 --> 22:05.889
- What about it?

22:05.933 --> 22:08.022
- We're trying to track
Graham down.

22:08.065 --> 22:10.329
- Best of luck with that.

22:10.372 --> 22:12.548
- Look, I know
it's a long shot,

22:12.592 --> 22:15.029
but if you know anything,
it'd be really appreciated.

22:17.205 --> 22:19.033
Did Graham ever play here?

22:19.076 --> 22:20.643
- Of course he did.

22:20.687 --> 22:22.428
I knew he was special
from the beginning.

22:22.471 --> 22:25.474
In fact, I gave Graham
his first chess set for free

22:25.518 --> 22:27.041
since he couldn't afford one.

22:27.084 --> 22:29.522
- So, when's the last time
you saw him?

22:29.565 --> 22:31.915
- Same as anyone.
About ten years ago.

22:38.052 --> 22:39.401
- Wow.

22:39.445 --> 22:42.491
Where did you get
all of this stuff?

22:42.535 --> 22:45.320
- Other collectors mostly.

22:45.364 --> 22:47.975
They're all authentic if that's
what you're worried about.

22:48.018 --> 22:49.498
- Judge.

22:50.456 --> 22:52.240
- Let me know if there's
anything you like.

22:53.763 --> 22:55.112
- This is a dead end, bro.

22:55.156 --> 22:56.679
Let's just go back
to IdentitySeal

22:56.723 --> 22:58.899
and run "John Turner"
through the database.

23:01.423 --> 23:03.425
- We don't have to.

23:03.469 --> 23:06.733
Look at the return label.
"John Turner."

23:06.776 --> 23:09.257
That's why Larry has so many of
Graham Hastings items for sale,

23:09.300 --> 23:11.390
because he's getting them
from Graham himself.

23:11.433 --> 23:12.434
[camera snaps]

23:12.478 --> 23:14.131
Got it.

23:14.175 --> 23:17.134
[light suspenseful music]

23:17.178 --> 23:22.749
♪

23:33.063 --> 23:34.413
- Can I help you?

23:34.456 --> 23:38.417
- Uh...you're Graham Hastings.

23:38.460 --> 23:41.637
- Look, I just wanna be
left alone.

23:41.681 --> 23:42.856
I don't know how you found me.

23:42.899 --> 23:44.684
- Wait--h-hold on.

23:44.727 --> 23:46.947
We're here because
of Aleksander Leff.

23:49.036 --> 23:52.648
Please.
Just hear us out.

24:01.178 --> 24:02.615
- So what does
Aleksander want?

24:02.658 --> 24:05.356
- Honestly,
we don't know that.

24:05.400 --> 24:07.358
We were kind of hoping
you could tell us.

24:07.402 --> 24:10.405
- I have no idea.
And to be honest, I don't care.

24:11.754 --> 24:13.364
You can tell Aleksander I have

24:13.408 --> 24:15.410
no interest in reliving
the past.

24:15.454 --> 24:17.934
[solemn music]

24:17.978 --> 24:19.893
- He's sick.

24:21.851 --> 24:24.463
He doesn't have much time.

24:30.251 --> 24:32.079
- I'm sorry to hear that.

24:32.122 --> 24:35.125
I really am, but it doesn't
change anything.

24:35.169 --> 24:37.214
- You won't even talk to him?

24:39.347 --> 24:43.656
- I know how hard
that loss was.

24:43.699 --> 24:45.658
Everyone does.

24:45.701 --> 24:47.790
- You think you understand
what happened that day?

24:47.834 --> 24:49.096
- No, no.
I don't.

24:49.139 --> 24:50.793
Please, explain it to me.

24:52.403 --> 24:55.058
- To most people,
chess is just a game.

24:56.712 --> 24:59.933
But to a few of us, it means
something so much more.

25:02.501 --> 25:04.503
My grandfather raised me.

25:04.546 --> 25:05.982
Man never graduated
high school,

25:06.026 --> 25:07.506
but he knew the game.

25:07.549 --> 25:09.725
And when he saw
what I could do,

25:09.769 --> 25:13.120
he knew it was my ticket
to a better life.

25:13.163 --> 25:14.904
Chess doesn't care about
the color of your skin

25:14.948 --> 25:17.037
or how much money you have.

25:17.080 --> 25:20.083
All it cares about
is how good you are.

25:21.345 --> 25:22.999
The more people told me
how good I was,

25:23.043 --> 25:25.219
that I was unbeatable,
the more I believed them.

25:26.873 --> 25:29.310
And then when I lost
to Aleksander,

25:29.353 --> 25:31.312
that all changed.

25:31.355 --> 25:33.880
- But it was just one loss.

25:33.923 --> 25:35.577
- You don't get it.

25:35.621 --> 25:36.839
Since I was a kid,
people told me

25:36.883 --> 25:38.624
I was the next Bobby Fischer.

25:38.667 --> 25:40.495
You hear it so long,
you start to believe it.

25:42.323 --> 25:45.500
But after I lost, that's all
anyone wanted to talk about.

25:45.544 --> 25:47.197
Shattered my confidence.

25:47.241 --> 25:50.461
I thought if I played
in a few local tournaments

25:50.505 --> 25:52.072
under assumed names,

25:52.115 --> 25:54.988
played in a park with people
who didn't recognize me...

25:55.031 --> 25:56.598
- You could get it back.

25:58.992 --> 26:00.863
- But I kept losing.

26:00.907 --> 26:04.388
I realized I lost more
than confidence.

26:04.432 --> 26:06.521
I lost my love for the game.

26:08.305 --> 26:11.178
So, yes, I walked away.

26:11.221 --> 26:12.832
Never looked back.

26:12.875 --> 26:14.877
- Maybe talking to Aleksander
will bring you some peace.

26:14.921 --> 26:16.226
- How?

26:16.270 --> 26:17.576
I don't blame him
for what happened.

26:17.619 --> 26:19.360
- Maybe he does.

26:19.403 --> 26:21.014
He went to a whole lot
of trouble to try to find you.

26:21.057 --> 26:23.407
All you have to do is listen.

26:25.018 --> 26:26.933
You were his best friend.

26:33.243 --> 26:35.898
- Tell him to come over
tonight.

26:35.942 --> 26:38.379
- We will.

26:38.422 --> 26:41.774
♪

26:41.817 --> 26:43.732
- Sorry, sorry.
One more super quick thing.

26:43.776 --> 26:47.518
You wouldn't happen to know
the name Falken, would you?

26:47.562 --> 26:50.043
- Falken?

26:50.086 --> 26:52.349
No, sorry.

26:59.182 --> 27:00.706
- You know, I'm glad you
found him and all,

27:00.749 --> 27:01.837
but you should have called me.

27:01.881 --> 27:03.360
- Us.
- Us--right.

27:03.404 --> 27:06.450
We were working on this
together.

27:06.494 --> 27:08.539
It's kind of a breach
of the private detective

27:08.583 --> 27:10.019
code of conduct, to be honest.

27:10.063 --> 27:13.414
- I'm sorry, okay?
It all happened so fast.

27:13.457 --> 27:15.634
As soon as we saw the name
on that return address,

27:15.677 --> 27:17.287
we just raced over there.

27:17.331 --> 27:20.116
The private detective
code of conduct?

27:20.160 --> 27:21.814
You are making that up,
aren't you?

27:21.857 --> 27:24.904
- What gave it away?
- What's up, guys?

27:24.947 --> 27:28.168
- Oh, Ali, this is Ray.
Ray, this is my sister, Ali.

27:28.211 --> 27:29.778
- Pleasure.
- Ray's a PI.

27:29.822 --> 27:31.301
We helped him on a case
a while back,

27:31.345 --> 27:32.694
though I doubt he would
admit that.

27:32.738 --> 27:34.261
- Yeah, yeah.
Fine, you know what?

27:34.304 --> 27:37.264
As a thank you, why don't I
buy us a round?

27:37.307 --> 27:39.962
Assuming that
it's happy hour prices?

27:40.006 --> 27:42.878
- I think I can ring up
a family and friends discount.

27:42.922 --> 27:45.925
[phone buzzing]

27:47.056 --> 27:48.710
- Ray Nicolette.

27:48.754 --> 27:50.059
Yeah.

27:51.365 --> 27:53.019
Ah, damn.

27:54.063 --> 27:55.891
Are you okay?

27:56.892 --> 27:58.851
Yeah, I understand.

27:58.894 --> 28:01.331
That was Aleksander's wife.

28:01.375 --> 28:02.898
He's in the hospital.

28:02.942 --> 28:04.073
- Is he okay?

28:04.117 --> 28:05.553
- She says he's stable,

28:05.596 --> 28:07.207
but he's not in any shape
to meet Graham.

28:07.250 --> 28:08.556
At least not at his house

28:08.599 --> 28:10.036
- Okay, well, we'll bring
Graham to him.

28:10.079 --> 28:11.385
- Good idea.

28:12.734 --> 28:15.128
- Miles
- Dad.

28:16.738 --> 28:19.306
This is Ray Nicolette.
- Hi, I'm Arthur.

28:19.349 --> 28:21.264
- Pleasure.
Is this like a family bar, or?

28:21.308 --> 28:22.657
[laughter]

28:22.701 --> 28:23.919
- Cara and I were just
heading out.

28:23.963 --> 28:25.704
We found Graham Hastings.

28:26.922 --> 28:28.619
- You're kidding.
- No.

28:28.663 --> 28:30.796
We're heading to reunite him
with Aleksander Leff.

28:30.839 --> 28:32.711
- All right.
So, tomorrow, chess.

28:32.754 --> 28:34.321
You tell me all about it.

28:34.364 --> 28:35.888
- I'll be there.
- All right.

28:37.150 --> 28:40.370
- Are you kidding?
I just opened three beers.

28:40.414 --> 28:42.198
- That's not gonna be
a problem.

28:42.242 --> 28:43.765
- Hey, darling.
- Hi, Dad.

28:43.809 --> 28:45.201
- Hey, beer Arthur?

28:45.245 --> 28:46.986
- Thank you.
Don't mind if I do.

28:48.161 --> 28:50.380
So, how do you and Miles
know each other?

28:50.424 --> 28:53.819
- That is one hell of a story
actually.

28:53.862 --> 28:56.386
- Well, isn't that why people
come to a bar,

28:56.430 --> 28:58.214
to hear a good story?

29:00.739 --> 29:02.958
- My wife Abby died a year ago,

29:03.002 --> 29:05.613
and for reasons that sound
absolutely insane

29:05.656 --> 29:08.137
when you say it out loud...

29:08.181 --> 29:10.923
I think she sent your son
to help me through it.

29:10.966 --> 29:13.055
[soft music]

29:13.099 --> 29:14.796
- Oh.

29:14.840 --> 29:18.321
Oh, does this have something
to do with the God Account?

29:18.365 --> 29:19.714
- Mm-hmm.
Yep.

29:19.758 --> 29:21.324
A couple months ago
they sent him my name.

29:21.368 --> 29:23.065
Now Graham's.

29:23.109 --> 29:26.416
Apparently a hell of a lot
of people in between.

29:26.460 --> 29:28.331
You know, I don't know
who's behind it all.

29:28.375 --> 29:30.203
I don't know why
they chose your son.

29:30.246 --> 29:32.379
But I do know this:

29:32.422 --> 29:35.208
that kid's making
a hell of a difference.

29:35.251 --> 29:36.557
- Huh.

29:36.600 --> 29:42.650
♪

29:42.693 --> 29:44.217
- I'm sorry to interrupt,

29:44.260 --> 29:46.785
but there's someone here
to see you.

29:50.440 --> 29:53.095
- Hello, Aleksander.

29:53.139 --> 29:54.444
Been a while.

29:55.968 --> 29:57.360
- I'm sorry it took
something like this

29:57.404 --> 29:59.319
for me to finally reach out.

30:00.973 --> 30:02.452
- How you feeling?

30:02.496 --> 30:04.063
- Been better.

30:14.073 --> 30:16.815
There's something
you need to know

30:16.858 --> 30:19.295
about our last game.

30:19.339 --> 30:22.037
I so desperately wanted
to beat you.

30:24.866 --> 30:27.173
- I'm not sure I'm following.

30:27.216 --> 30:29.915
I was there that day, remember?

30:29.958 --> 30:32.439
You beat me, fair and square.

30:32.482 --> 30:33.919
- No, I didn't.

30:33.962 --> 30:36.965
[solemn music]

30:39.011 --> 30:42.797
A couple days before our match,

30:42.841 --> 30:44.799
I came across your chess
journals.

30:44.843 --> 30:47.019
- You read my journals?

30:47.062 --> 30:50.674
- I knew that you recorded
every game you played,

30:50.718 --> 30:52.676
every move of your opponent.

30:57.159 --> 31:00.554
I came across your notes
on a game we'd recently played.

31:00.597 --> 31:04.993
You'd made a note that
I had missed a move,

31:05.037 --> 31:08.301
one that would have set me up
to beat you.

31:09.650 --> 31:12.087
- You recreated the game.

31:12.131 --> 31:14.829
- The only reason I won
that day,

31:14.873 --> 31:17.179
was because you showed me how.

31:18.311 --> 31:21.053
- You were my only friend.

31:21.096 --> 31:23.794
You knew more than anyone
I had nothing but chess.

31:23.838 --> 31:25.927
Nothing.
- Look, I'm sorry.

31:25.971 --> 31:30.453
I never thought losing
one game would do that to you.

31:30.497 --> 31:33.065
♪

31:33.108 --> 31:37.156
- You took away the one thing
I loved most.

31:39.114 --> 31:41.073
You took it all away.

31:42.639 --> 31:44.990
If you're looking
for absolution,

31:45.033 --> 31:47.514
I won't give it to you.

31:47.557 --> 31:53.085
♪

31:53.128 --> 31:54.782
- Graham.
Graham--wait.

31:54.825 --> 31:56.262
Please.
Wait.

31:56.305 --> 31:57.654
Graham--

31:57.698 --> 31:58.829
- There's nothing more
to say here.

31:58.873 --> 32:00.222
- There is so much more to say.

32:00.266 --> 32:01.528
You haven't even given
him a chance.

32:01.571 --> 32:03.356
- Why do I need to give him
a chance?

32:03.399 --> 32:05.836
He's the one who stole the last
ten years of my life from me.

32:05.880 --> 32:07.751
- I get that. I do.

32:07.795 --> 32:10.885
But maybe his apology is a way
for you to get chess back.

32:10.929 --> 32:14.193
You said you couldn't
understand how he beat you.

32:14.236 --> 32:16.412
And not knowing made you
question everything

32:16.456 --> 32:18.501
you thought you knew
to be true.

32:18.545 --> 32:21.461
About you.
About the game.

32:21.504 --> 32:25.769
Now you have your answer.
You have the truth.

32:25.813 --> 32:28.468
Why not use this to reclaim
what you lost?

32:28.511 --> 32:29.991
- It's too late.

32:30.035 --> 32:31.471
That truth doesn't change
what happened.

32:31.514 --> 32:34.169
- But it could change
what will happen.

32:34.213 --> 32:38.130
If you don't at least try
to forgive him,

32:38.173 --> 32:41.960
it might be a bigger mistake
than the one he made.

32:44.701 --> 32:46.877
- I'm sorry.

32:46.921 --> 32:48.749
I can't.

32:48.792 --> 32:50.620
I just can't.

32:50.664 --> 32:52.971
♪

33:02.545 --> 33:05.505
[solemn music]

33:05.548 --> 33:08.073
♪

33:08.116 --> 33:09.813
[elevator bell dings]

33:09.857 --> 33:16.690
♪

33:16.733 --> 33:18.866
- Damn it.

33:18.909 --> 33:25.873
♪

33:25.916 --> 33:28.919
[tapping]

33:32.488 --> 33:35.491
[tapping continues]

33:45.197 --> 33:52.204
♪

34:08.437 --> 34:11.092
- You're really gonna leave
your rook out there like that?

34:12.441 --> 34:13.790
- It's part of my plan.

34:13.834 --> 34:15.444
- You have a plan?

34:15.488 --> 34:16.706
- Is that a challenge?

34:16.750 --> 34:18.665
- No, I haven't played
in a while.

34:18.708 --> 34:21.146
- I could take it easy on you.

34:23.496 --> 34:26.107
- Thanks.

34:26.151 --> 34:33.158
♪

35:05.538 --> 35:07.235
- Check.

35:12.980 --> 35:15.548
- Who taught you how to play?
- My dad.

35:19.813 --> 35:22.990
- Is there anything we can do
for you before we go?

35:23.033 --> 35:24.905
- Thank you, no.

35:24.948 --> 35:26.515
You've already done so much.

35:28.213 --> 35:29.953
Annabelle,
where have you been?

35:29.997 --> 35:32.347
- She was playing chess...

35:32.391 --> 35:34.567
With me.

35:35.611 --> 35:37.439
- Come on, sweetheart.

35:37.483 --> 35:39.485
Let's give Daddy
and his friends a moment.

35:39.528 --> 35:43.358
♪

35:43.402 --> 35:45.969
- Is she part of the reason
you were searching for me?

35:46.013 --> 35:47.928
- Partly, yes.

35:49.669 --> 35:52.672
Her love of the game.
Her passion.

35:52.715 --> 35:56.763
Her God-given talent.

35:57.807 --> 35:59.157
I know what I stole,

35:59.200 --> 36:01.028
and I know I can
never give it back to you.

36:01.071 --> 36:05.119
But I'm hoping that maybe
she can.

36:05.163 --> 36:07.643
- What are you talking about?

36:07.687 --> 36:09.906
- She's going to need
a teacher.

36:13.388 --> 36:16.086
You're the only one I trust
to pass on the game

36:16.130 --> 36:18.306
that we both once loved.

36:20.134 --> 36:22.789
That I know you
could love again.

36:22.832 --> 36:24.660
- I don't know.

36:26.271 --> 36:28.186
It's gonna be hard work
getting Annabelle

36:28.229 --> 36:31.798
to lose all those bad habits
you taught you.

36:31.841 --> 36:34.931
[uplifting music]

36:34.975 --> 36:37.151
But I'll do my best.

36:38.544 --> 36:41.373
I'm just gonna need
one thing in return.

36:41.416 --> 36:43.331
- What's that?

36:43.375 --> 36:45.072
- A rematch.

36:45.115 --> 36:50.077
♪

36:52.297 --> 36:55.561
- ♪ I'll hope

36:55.604 --> 36:59.391
♪ So here I go

36:59.434 --> 37:01.915
♪ You change my world

37:01.958 --> 37:03.264
- Miles, Cara.

37:03.308 --> 37:05.745
♪

37:05.788 --> 37:07.529
I wanted to thank you.

37:07.573 --> 37:11.185
If you hadn't shown up today,
who knows what the next

37:11.229 --> 37:12.578
ten years would have
looked like.

37:12.621 --> 37:14.406
- I'm glad we could be
of some help.

37:14.449 --> 37:18.279
- Yeah, if there's anything
I can do for you, just ask.

37:18.323 --> 37:21.891
- Actually, there's one thing.

37:21.935 --> 37:25.112
I was kinda hoping to score
an interview.

37:25.155 --> 37:28.158
I think people wanna hear
your story.

37:28.202 --> 37:31.597
♪

37:31.640 --> 37:33.990
- I guess it's time to tell it.

37:34.034 --> 37:36.341
Come by the apartment tomorrow.
We'll talk.

37:36.384 --> 37:38.430
Oh, one last thing.

37:38.473 --> 37:41.346
Earlier, your friend asked
if I knew Falken.

37:41.389 --> 37:44.000
I do--or at least I did.

37:44.044 --> 37:47.265
I didn't tell you before,
because I didn't know you.

37:47.308 --> 37:49.615
We met at a tournament
15 years ago.

37:49.658 --> 37:51.660
He approached me
and said he was building

37:51.704 --> 37:53.183
a special kind of computer.

37:53.227 --> 37:54.620
Wanted me to play chess
against it.

37:54.663 --> 37:56.752
I was intrigued, so I did.

37:56.796 --> 38:00.103
Beat the damn thing every time.
Though, it did get better.

38:00.147 --> 38:03.281
After a few months,
he thanked me

38:03.324 --> 38:06.196
and I never saw or heard
from him again.

38:06.240 --> 38:07.546
Of course, when I met him,

38:07.589 --> 38:09.765
he was still going by his
given name.

38:09.809 --> 38:11.767
The "Falken" thing came later.

38:13.116 --> 38:15.597
- Wait, you know Falken's
real name?

38:16.381 --> 38:17.947
- What was it?

38:17.991 --> 38:19.819
- Henry Chase.

38:19.862 --> 38:22.256
Hope that helps.

38:22.300 --> 38:23.649
- Thanks.

38:23.692 --> 38:25.651
- Whew.

38:28.044 --> 38:29.481
What until we tell Rakesh.

38:29.524 --> 38:31.744
- Yeah, his mind
is going to explode.

38:33.441 --> 38:37.358
[Echosmith's "Bright"]

38:37.402 --> 38:39.447
- ♪ I think the universe

38:39.491 --> 38:41.493
♪ Is on my side

38:41.536 --> 38:43.495
- We live our lives thinking

38:43.538 --> 38:46.193
we need to leave something
behind before we die.

38:46.236 --> 38:50.328
But a person's legacy can mean
so many different things.

38:50.371 --> 38:52.852
It's the shared experiences

38:52.895 --> 38:55.637
we all go through
that binds us together,

38:55.681 --> 38:58.771
paving the way
for new relationships.

38:58.814 --> 39:00.773
- [laughs]
Hey.

39:00.816 --> 39:02.862
What are you doing here?

39:02.905 --> 39:04.603
- I just wanted to come by
and see you.

39:04.646 --> 39:06.648
- Huh.

39:06.692 --> 39:09.869
Hey, uh, look,

39:09.912 --> 39:13.394
I like you.
I think you like me, too.

39:13.438 --> 39:17.398
But if there's something
that you're holding back--

39:17.442 --> 39:21.184
- ♪ ooh la la la

39:21.228 --> 39:24.536
♪ You make a girl go ooh

39:24.579 --> 39:26.581
♪ I'm in love

39:26.625 --> 39:28.409
- While also reminding us

39:28.453 --> 39:30.672
it's never too late
to mend the past.

39:30.716 --> 39:33.240
- ♪ Star tonight

39:33.283 --> 39:34.763
♪ Were you dazzled

39:34.807 --> 39:37.157
- And hope for the future.

39:37.200 --> 39:39.551
- If we're going to play
this game,

39:39.594 --> 39:42.641
then let's call each other
by our first names.

39:42.684 --> 39:45.818
Nice to meet you, Henry.

39:45.861 --> 39:49.952
- ♪ And I see colors
in a different way ♪

39:49.996 --> 39:52.999
♪ You make what
doesn't matter ♪

39:53.042 --> 39:56.219
♪ Fade to gray

39:56.263 --> 39:58.570
♪ Life is good

39:58.613 --> 40:02.835
♪ And that's the way
it should be ♪

40:02.878 --> 40:05.577
♪

40:05.620 --> 40:07.709
- Hey there, Annabelle.

40:07.753 --> 40:10.538
Do you see what
your father just did?

40:10.582 --> 40:13.106
- He lost his queen.

40:13.149 --> 40:15.674
- I did not.

40:15.717 --> 40:18.851
- Maybe not yet,
but in four moves you will.

40:18.894 --> 40:20.896
- And if we're lucky enough,

40:20.940 --> 40:23.638
We get to see
the lessons of our life

40:23.682 --> 40:26.598
passed down to those
we love most.

40:26.641 --> 40:31.994
♪

40:32.038 --> 40:33.431
- Is it everything
you hoped for?

40:33.474 --> 40:35.998
- Better.
[chuckles]

40:36.042 --> 40:37.652
- That's the thing
about legacy.

40:39.524 --> 40:41.177
It's never too late
to change it

40:41.221 --> 40:42.831
or make it better.

40:42.875 --> 40:44.529
You just have to know
where to start.

40:44.572 --> 40:46.792
- ♪ Star tonight

40:46.835 --> 40:49.490
♪ Were you dazzled
by the same...♪

40:49.534 --> 40:51.144
[knock at door]

40:51.187 --> 40:55.453
♪ Did you and Jupiter
conspire ♪

40:55.496 --> 40:56.932
- Dad, hey.
- Hey.

40:56.976 --> 40:58.630
- Is everything all right?
- Uh, yeah.

40:58.673 --> 40:59.979
No, everything is fine.

41:00.022 --> 41:02.460
I was just hoping
we could talk.

41:02.503 --> 41:05.071
- ♪ I think you and the moon
and Neptune got it right ♪

41:05.114 --> 41:06.681
- I'd like to know
a little bit more

41:06.725 --> 41:09.336
about this God Account
of yours.

41:09.379 --> 41:11.643
♪

41:11.686 --> 41:14.167
- ♪ 'Cause now
I'm shining bright ♪

41:14.210 --> 41:15.690
- Come on in.

41:15.734 --> 41:17.866
- ♪ So bright

41:17.910 --> 41:24.699
♪
